Here is an example of how a table of contents (TOC) can be generated automatically in a LaTeX document using the `toc` package:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tocloft}
\usepackage{lipsum}

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}
\lipsum[1]

\subsection{Subsection 1}
\lipsum[2]

\subsection{Subsection 2}
\lipsum[3]

\section{Methods}
\lipsum[4]

\subsection{Subsection 3}
\lipsum[5]

\subsection{Subsection 4}
\lipsum[6]

\section{Results}
\lipsum[7]

\subsection{Subsection 5}
\lipsum[8]

\subsection{Subsection 6}
\lipsum[9]

\end{document}
```

In this example, the `\tableofcontents` command is used to generate the TOC. The `tocloft` package is used to customize the appearance of the TOC.

Here's a brief explanation of the commands used:

* `\documentclass{article}`: Specifies the document class.
* `\usepackage{tocloft}`: Loads the `tocloft` package, which provides additional features for customizing the TOC.
* `\usepackage{lipsum}`: Loads the `lipsum` package, which generates dummy text for demonstration purposes.
* `\tableofcontents`: Generates the TOC.
* `\section`, `\subsection`, etc.: Define the section and subsection headings.
* `\lipsum[1]`, `\lipsum[2]`, etc.: Generate dummy text using the `lipsum` package.

When you compile this document, you will see a TOC at the beginning of the document that lists the section and subsection headings.

